<paragraph id="8BD4B83EFF9FFFAD4092104A393A0D0E" blockId="14.[189,1400,337,1755]" box="[189,1399,337,364]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<keyLead id="309A1B0BFF9FFFAD4092104A393A0D0E" box="[189,1399,337,364]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">1. Erect propodeal setae brown or black............................................................................................2</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD4B83EFF9FFFAD40EE106D393B0DED" blockId="14.[189,1400,337,1755]" box="[193,1398,372,399]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<keyLead id="309A1B0BFF9FFFAD40EE106D393B0DED" box="[193,1398,372,399]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">– Erect propodeal setae silvery or golden..........................................................................................5</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="309FA09BFF9FFFAD409210A639380E23" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<paragraph id="8BD4B83EFF9FFFAD409210A6393B0D99" blockId="14.[189,1400,337,1755]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<keyLead id="309A1B0BFF9FFFAD409210A6393B0D99" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
2. Cellular wing area with yellow or ferruginous tinge; wing base not notably infuscate (
<figureCitation id="1350A4BBFF9FFFAD452410A63D460D9E" captionStart="Figs 57–62. 57, 60–61" captionStartId="54.[189,241,1890,1916]" captionTargetBox="[228,1336,265,1862]" captionTargetId="figure-83@54.[228,1359,265,1864]" captionTargetPageId="54" captionText="Figs 57–62. 57, 60–61. Sphex tomentosus Fabricius, 1787, ♂. 58. S. torridus F. Smith, 1873, habitus of ♀. 59. S. voeltzkowii Kohl, 1909, habitus of ♂. 57. Habitus. 60. Dorsal view of genitalia. 61. Lateral view of penis valvae. 62. Geographic distribution of S. voeltzkowii (red), S. caeruleanus Drury, 1773 (blue), S. mweruensis (Arnold, 1947) (yellow) and S. hades sp. nov. (purple)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6299460" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6299460/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Figs 58– 59</figureCitation>
). 
<collectingCountry id="F37CF8AEFF9FFFAD410A10F93DFE0D99" box="[293,435,481,507]" name="Madagascar" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
and surrounding islands only..............................................................................3
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD4B83EFF9FFFAD40EE131D39380E23" blockId="14.[189,1400,337,1755]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<keyLead id="309A1B0BFF9FFFAD40EE131D39380E23" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
– Cellular wing area without yellow tinge; wing base markedly fuscous (
<figureCitation id="1350A4BBFF9FFFAD4469131C38990E7D" box="[1094,1236,516,543]" captionStart="Figs 49–56. 49" captionStartId="41.[189,241,1843,1869]" captionTargetBox="[189,1399,265,1815]" captionTargetId="figure-99@41.[189,1399,265,1817]" captionTargetPageId="41" captionText="Figs 49–56. 49. Sphex fumicatus Christ, 1791, habitus of ♀. 50. S. lanatus Mocsáry, 1883, habitus of ♀. 51. S. rufinervis Pérez, 1895, habitus of ♂. 52. S. taschenbergi Magretti, 1884, habitus of ♀. 53. S. fumicatus, frontal view of ♀. 54. S. taschenbergi, frontal view of ♀. 55. Geographic distribution of S. lanatus (red), S. rufinervis (blue) and S. taschenbergi (yellow). 56. Geographic distribution of S. tomentosus Fabricius, 1787 (red) and S. torridus F. Smith, 1873 (blue)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6299458" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6299458/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Figs 49, 52</figureCitation>
). Widespread..........................................................................................................................................................4
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="309FA09BFF9FFFAD40921368393A0F75" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<paragraph id="8BD4B83EFF9FFFAD40921368393A0ECC" blockId="14.[189,1400,337,1755]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<keyLead id="309A1B0BFF9FFFAD40921368393A0ECC" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
3. Female: apical margin of fore- and hindwing completely fuscous (
<figureCitation id="1350A4BBFF9FFFAD4437136838390EE9" box="[1048,1140,624,651]" captionStart="Figs 57–62. 57, 60–61" captionStartId="54.[189,241,1890,1916]" captionTargetBox="[228,1336,265,1862]" captionTargetId="figure-83@54.[228,1359,265,1864]" captionTargetPageId="54" captionText="Figs 57–62. 57, 60–61. Sphex tomentosus Fabricius, 1787, ♂. 58. S. torridus F. Smith, 1873, habitus of ♀. 59. S. voeltzkowii Kohl, 1909, habitus of ♂. 57. Habitus. 60. Dorsal view of genitalia. 61. Lateral view of penis valvae. 62. Geographic distribution of S. voeltzkowii (red), S. caeruleanus Drury, 1773 (blue), S. mweruensis (Arnold, 1947) (yellow) and S. hades sp. nov. (purple)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6299460" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6299460/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Fig. 58</figureCitation>
). Male: erect clypeal and paraocular setae uniformly black ......................................................... 
<taxonomicName id="4C6BC3BDFF9FFFAD446A138B393A0ECC" authority="F. Smith, 1873" authorityName="F. Smith" authorityYear="1873" box="[1093,1399,659,686]" class="Insecta" family="Vespidae" genus="Sphex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="torridus">
<emphasis id="B91F642CFF9FFFAD446A138B38890ECC" bold="true" box="[1093,1220,659,686]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">S. torridus</emphasis>
F. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFFAC5CFFF9FFFAD44C8138B393A0ECC" author="Smith F." box="[1255,1399,659,686]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" pagination="253 - 260" refId="ref132053" refString="Smith F. 1873. Descriptions of new species of fossorial Hymenoptera in the collection of the British Museum, and of a species of the rare genus Iswara, belonging to the family Dorylidae. The Annals and Magazine of Natural History, Series 4 12: 253 - 260 (Sep.), 291 - 300 (Oct.), 402 - 415 (Oct.). https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222937308680752" type="journal article" year="1873">Smith, 1873</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD4B83EFF9FFFAD40EE13AF393A0F75" blockId="14.[189,1400,337,1755]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<keyLead id="309A1B0BFF9FFFAD40EE13AF393A0F75" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
– Female: apical margin of forewing only anteriorly with fuscous spot, apex of hindwing hyaline. Male: erect clypeal setae silvery intermixed with black ones; erect paraocular setae uniformly silvery-golden ............................................................................................. 
<taxonomicName id="4C6BC3BDFF9FFFAD446A13E5393A0F75" authority="Kohl, 1909" authorityName="Kohl" authorityYear="1909" box="[1093,1399,765,792]" class="Insecta" family="Vespidae" genus="Sphex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="voeltzkowii">
